e", "prob": 0.9139388799667358, "span": {"begin": 993, "end": 1011}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018754"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ventricular myocardium hypoplasia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999797344207764, "span": {"begin": 1022, "end": 1055}}, {"id": ["mesh:D020964"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "embryonic lethality", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999876022338867, "span": {"begin": 1069, "end": 1088}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Raldh2", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6632452011108398, "span": {"begin": 1283, "end": 1289}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8854"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Raldh2 mouse mutant", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8979113698005676, "span": {"begin": 1283, "end": 1302}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10090"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mouse", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.969689130783081, "span": {"begin": 1290, "end": 1295}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9905822277069092, "span": {"begin": 1475, "end": 1480}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014801"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "vitamin A", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997220635414124, "span": {"begin": 1484, "end": 1493}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9941108822822571, "span": {"begin": 1517, "end": 1521}}, {"id": ["mesh:C535853"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "conotruncal and aortic arch artery malformations", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999988675117493, "span": {"begin": 1552, "end": 1600}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014188"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "great vessel transposition", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9991270899772644, "span": {"begin": 1606, "end": 1632}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004310"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "right ventricle double outlet", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9997012615203857, "span": {"begin": 1634, "end": 1663}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014286"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "teratology of Fallot", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999961853027344, "span": {"begin": 1669, "end": 1689}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ATRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9960517287254333, "span": {"begin": 1777, "end": 1781}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014178"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "transposition of", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.7191087603569031, "span": {"begin": 1792, "end": 1808}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SHF progenitors", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.4657779633998871, "span": {"begin": 1954, "end": 1969}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8854"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Aldh1a2KO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9842296242713928, "span": {"begin": 2020, "end": 2029}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9532250165939331, "span": {"begin": 2030, "end": 2034}}], "text": "The evidence for the relationship of ATRA gradient formation and SHF patterning is well established and nicely summarized by Nakajima (2019). The posterior part of the SHF is in need of a strong ATRA signaling that inhibits Tbx1 to define the posterior SHF boundary. Low-weak ATRA signaling stimulates the expression of Tbx1 in the anterior SHF. The anterior SHF consists of progenitors for the formation of the outflow tract (OFT). Additionally, the anterior SHF&rsquo;s cranial segments consisting of pharyngeal arches 1-2 and are responsible for the formation of the right ventricle and proximal OFT. The anterior SHF&rsquo;s caudal segments consisting of the pharyngeal arches 3-6 are responsible for distal OFT formation and the ascending aorta (AA). The aortic arch within pharyngeal arch 4 will eventually form the ascending aorta.   Evidence for this relationship mainly comes from knockout studies. Mutations of the Rdh and Raldh2 gene result in phenotypes characterized by prominent myocardial defects as severe ventricular myocardium hypoplasia resulting in embryonic lethality (Brade et al., 2011; el Robrini et al., 2016; Merki et al., 2005; Niederreither et al., 1997, 2001; Sorrell &amp; Waxman, 2011; Stefanovic &amp; Zaffran, 2017; S. Wang &amp; Moise, 2019). These Raldh2 mouse mutant embryos show a disruption of the posterior limit of the SHF starting at E7.5 (Duong &amp; Waxman, 2021; Ryckebusch et al., 2008a; Sirbu et al., 2008).   Excess exposure in human to vitamin A or the analogues (e.g. ATRA), can cause defects including conotruncal and aortic arch artery malformations like great vessel transposition, right ventricle double outlet, and teratology of Fallot (Stefanovic &amp; Zaffran, 2017). This is also observed when rodents were treated with ATRA including transposition of great arteries and patterning defects (Stefanovic &amp; Zaffran, 2017). In vitro experiments confirmed the in vivo observations because cultured SHF progenitors failed to differentiate from the arterial pole of Aldh1a2KO mice (Ryckebusch et al., 2008b).  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:38:42 +0000 2026"}